text:
 Find Supplies Pick up crown molding from a local lumber or hardware store. You want molding with ridges and/or texture. Envision setting a taco on the crown molding before you purchase it so you obtain the right one. Consider getting pre-stained or painted molding so you can omit having to paint it. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/5\/5f\/Use-Crown-Moldings-to-Hold-Tacos-Step-1Bullet1.jpg\/v4-459px-Use-Crown-Moldings-to-Hold-Tacos-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/5\/5f\/Use-Crown-Moldings-to-Hold-Tacos-Step-1Bullet1.jpg\/v4-759px-Use-Crown-Moldings-to-Hold-Tacos-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Pick up paint, gloss or stain if the molding you choose is still “naked.”{"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/a7\/Use-Crown-Moldings-to-Hold-Tacos-Step-1Bullet2.jpg\/v4-459px-Use-Crown-Moldings-to-Hold-Tacos-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/a7\/Use-Crown-Moldings-to-Hold-Tacos-Step-1Bullet2.jpg\/v4-759px-Use-Crown-Moldings-to-Hold-Tacos-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Get enough molding to hold 6 or more tacos at one time. Make this serving tray worth you while so you aren’t constantly restocking. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/34\/Use-Crown-Moldings-to-Hold-Tacos-Step-1Bullet3.jpg\/v4-459px-Use-Crown-Moldings-to-Hold-Tacos-Step-1Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/34\/Use-Crown-Moldings-to-Hold-Tacos-Step-1Bullet3.jpg\/v4-759px-Use-Crown-Moldings-to-Hold-Tacos-Step-1Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"} Purchase a pre-made wooden box or make one yourself. The box should be the same width and length of the crown molding, so it may be in your best interest to make your own. Take measurements of the box width and length before purchasing enough plywood to create the box. Have the hardware store pre-cut pieces so all you will need to do is assemble it. Take into consideration how you’d like to assemble the box and pick up necessary supplies. You will need enough material to form the box but you won’t need a top (you can turn the box upside down). In some cases you could use wood glue and glue the box together. However, nailing it together, using small nails might be your best bet. Pick up both small nails and wood glue as you will also be securing the molding to the box. You’ll want to have options in the event one method does not work very well. Purchase stain or paint for the box. You may want to select a color to compliment the crown molding. Create the Taco Stand Clean and/or sand crown moldings. You will be placing food on this wood so you want to make sure no debris or rough edges are on the moldings. If sanding is required, sand first and then clean with warm water and mild dish detergent. Paint, gloss or stain moldings if you did not purchase pre-painted wood. Consider adding a final gloss coat at the end to seal the wood and protect it from food spills. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/37\/Use-Crown-Moldings-to-Hold-Tacos-Step-4Bullet1.jpg\/v4-459px-Use-Crown-Moldings-to-Hold-Tacos-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/37\/Use-Crown-Moldings-to-Hold-Tacos-Step-4Bullet1.jpg\/v4-759px-Use-Crown-Moldings-to-Hold-Tacos-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Allow ample dry time before securing it to the box. Assemble the box. Secure the sides together with wood glue and possibly following up with small nails. Stain or paint the box. Be sure you allow plenty of time for it to dry before completing the final step. Glue the crown molding to the box. Turn the box upside down so the open top is on the surface and the back is facing upward. Add a copious amount of glue to the top of the box and then gently set the crown molding in place. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/d\/d8\/Use-Crown-Moldings-to-Hold-Tacos-Step-6Bullet1.jpg\/v4-459px-Use-Crown-Moldings-to-Hold-Tacos-Step-6Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/d\/d8\/Use-Crown-Moldings-to-Hold-Tacos-Step-6Bullet1.jpg\/v4-759px-Use-Crown-Moldings-to-Hold-Tacos-Step-6Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}
